<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="24" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,1836,2004]" pageId="2" pageNumber="24">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1944,1968]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="24" reason="1">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific epithet is a Latin adjective (=smallest) referring to the small size of this species (see below).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="25" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,151,284]" pageId="3" pageNumber="25">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,321,151,176]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="25" reason="1">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
This species is similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Ruiz, 2011" authorityName="Ruiz" authorityYear="2011" box="[615,777,152,176]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Soesilarishius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="3" pageNumber="25" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="crispiventer" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[615,777,152,176]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="25">S. crispiventer</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[784,874,152,176]" pageId="3" pageNumber="25">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[784,874,152,176]" pageId="3" pageNumber="25" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
for the small size and boxy carapace (see 
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 6–9" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1839,1862]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,331,1815]" captionTargetId="figure-149@3.[151,1436,331,1815]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 6–9. Soesilarishius minimus sp. nov. 6 male habitus (paratype IBSP 160758); 7 female habitus (paratype IBSP 160711). Soesilarishius crispiventer sp. nov. 8 male habitus (paratype IBSP 160801); 9 female habitus (paratype IBSP 160841)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5280704" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5280704/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="25">Figs 6– 7, 8–9</figureCitation>
), but can easily be distinguished from that and the remaining known species by having a small, spiraled embolus in the male palp (
<figureCitation box="[445,512,223,247]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–5" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1738,1761]" captionTargetBox="[164,1400,426,1701]" captionTargetId="figure-151@2.[151,1436,410,1714]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–5. Soesilarishius aurifrons (Taczanowski) comb. nov. 1 left male palp, ventral. Soesilarishius minimus sp. nov. 2–3 left male palp (2 ventral, 3 retrolateral); 4 epigyne, ventral view; 5 vulva, dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5280702" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5280702/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="25">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
) and fertilization ducts arising from elongate projections dorsally to the large spermathecae in the epigyne (
<figureCitation box="[437,506,260,284]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–5" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1738,1761]" captionTargetBox="[164,1400,426,1701]" captionTargetId="figure-151@2.[151,1436,410,1714]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–5. Soesilarishius aurifrons (Taczanowski) comb. nov. 1 left male palp, ventral. Soesilarishius minimus sp. nov. 2–3 left male palp (2 ventral, 3 retrolateral); 4 epigyne, ventral view; 5 vulva, dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5280702" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5280702/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="25">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
